%%----------------------------------------------------------------------

Page Size and Margins

These macros make it easy to set the margins for a chosen paper size.
Two sided printing is supported, meaning if on odd pages the left
margin is, say, 30mm and the right margin is 20mm, it will be vice
versa on even pages. This gives equal margins on the outer and the
inner edge of the paper.

To use this style first select a paper size with 

	\setpapersize{<size>}

<size> can be Afour, Bfive, USletter, ... A list of the pre-defined
paper sizes is at the beginning of this file. If you have a size which
is not pre-defined use

	\setpapersize{custom}{<width>}{<height>}

For <width> and <height> insert the respective dimensions of your
paper. The length variables

	\paperwidth
	\paperheight

always contain the current papersize. Then the margins can be set with

	\setmargins{leftmargin}{topmargin}{textwidth}{textheight}%
  		   {headheight}{headsep}{footheight}{footskip}

or with

	\setmarginsrb{leftmargin}{topmargin}{rightmargin}{bottommargin}%
		     {headheight}{headsep}{footheight}{footskip}

Example:

A4 paper, left margin 30mm, top, right, and bottom margin 20mm each, no
headers or footers:

  \setpapersize{Afour}
  \setmarginsrb{30mm}{20mm}{20mm}{20mm}{0pt}{0mm}{0pt}{0mm}

The default is A4 paper, 25mm left margin, 20mm top, right, bottom
margins, ... Please see the part after DEFAULT.  This style also sets
several other paragraph parameters to new values.

These macros work fine with dvips. Apparently +1in is always added to the top and left margins, so

	\margin@offset

compensates for this by setting \topmargin, \oddsidemargin,
\evensidemargin top -1in. This is only done if \margin@offset is
undefined! If different margin offsets are desired \margin@offset can
be defined in a separate file which is included BEFORE Vpage.

